<sn><md>#### Religion

::: .row

::: .col-md-8

Pharaoh `Amenhotep IV` promoted the worship of a `single Sun God` instead of the traditional polytheistic belief system. The Sun God was named `Aten`.

To reflect this religious reform, he changed his own name to `Akhenaten`. Through this movement, Akhenaten is often regarded as one of the earliest rulers in history to promote the idea of `monotheism`.


:::

::: .col-md-4

![img](https://images.aeonmedia.co/images/25ea945e-ea0f-423a-8340-9ceb9877f0f6/essay-6946.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto)

:::

:::


```text id="xjfsyl"
Religion
      |
      +--&gt; Pharaoh Amenhotep IV
              |
              +--&gt; Aten (Sun God)
              |
              +--&gt; Akhenaten
                      |
                      +--&gt; Concept of Monotheism
```</md></sn><sn><md>#### Architecture and Sculpture

::: .row

::: .col-12 .col-md-6

In ancient Egypt, kings were known as `Pharaohs`. Egyptians believed in the existence of life after death, where the king would continue his existence as a Pharaoh.

For the preservation of the **mortal body of Pharaohs**, the `Pyramids` were constructed. The pyramids are considered the `oldest monumental structures in the world`. The largest pyramid in Egypt is the pyramid of `Pharaoh Khufu`, built over an area of about `13` acres with a height of approximately `450 feet`.

:::

::: .col-12 .col-md-6

![img](https://cdn.create.vista.com/api/media/small/188327392/stock-photo-the-great-pyramids-at-giza)

:::

:::

---

::: .row

::: .col-12 .col-md-6

![img](https://media.gettyimages.com/id/513613977/photo/great-sphinx-and-pyramid-of-khafre.jpg?s=612x612\&amp;w=0\&amp;k=20\&amp;c=Fx7Uv4FLI9vr7qvXsC9zsRmz2qbFElDkyW9LGY3L9Mk=)

:::

::: .col-12 .col-md-6

The greatest achievement of Egyptian sculpture is the `Sphinx`. It was carved on massive stone blocks. The Sphinx has the `body of a lion` and the `head of a Pharaoh`, symbolizing royal power and authority.

:::

:::

---

::: .row

::: .col-12 .col-md-6

Pharaoh `Tutankhamun` ruled Egypt from `1333–1324 BCE`. <br>
In `1922`, **Howard Carter** discovered his tomb, which created worldwide sensation.

:::

::: .col-12 .col-md-6

![img](https://www.historytoday.com/sites/default/files/tutankhamun.jpg)

:::

:::

